-- One creature_template entry per profession (900213-900226) - each a
-- standalone trainer teaching that profession's full 0/1-to-max skill
-- chain. Sliced from the same aggregated-from-every-real-trainer data this
-- module's original single all-professions NPC (entry 900200, since
-- retired - see premium_menu_item.lua and profession_trainer.lua for the
-- per-profession picker that replaced it) used to use in full -
-- deduplicated by spell, ordered low-to-high skill rank within each
-- profession. Values (cost/req level/req skill) copied verbatim from
-- whichever real trainer(s) already teach each spell.
--
-- Earlier draft of this redesign tried summoning a real, existing "Grand
-- Master" trainer creature directly instead (no new SQL at all, same
-- ENTRIES-style pattern Class Trainer uses) - reverted. This server runs
-- mod-individual-progression (confirmed enabled in
-- individualProgression.conf), and several real "Grand Master" trainers'
-- own trainer_spell rows in this server's acore_world turned out to
-- already span the *entire* skill range (e.g. Grand Master Blacksmithing,
-- TrainerId 59, teaches from ReqSkillRank 1) - which contradicts Wowhead's
-- retail WotLK reference data for the same NPC (Journeyman/50+ only) and
-- couldn't be conclusively explained (mod-individual-progression's own
-- professions.sql references TrainerId 59 in a comment but doesn't appear
-- to edit it; no runtime/per-phase trainer_spell rewriting exists in that
-- module's C++ source either, so whatever's live is at least static, but
-- its origin is unverifiable from SQL alone). Rather than build 14
-- creature_template entries on real data of uncertain provenance, all 14
-- use this module's own already-trusted aggregate instead - the data this
-- project has already verified against multiple real trainers and run in
-- production.
--
-- Uses the trainer/trainer_spell/creature_default_trainer schema that
-- ObjectMgr::LoadTrainers() actually reads (confirmed via source) - NOT
-- the older npc_trainer table, which still holds real data but is no
-- longer read by the trainer-loading code in this AzerothCore version.

-- Model/unit_class borrowed from each profession's own real "Grand
-- Master"-named trainer creature (model/displayId only, per this
-- project's hard invariant - none of those rows are ever modified):
-- 900213 Alchemy        <- Lanolis Dewdrop      (entry 26903)
-- 900214 Enchanting     <- Elizabeth Jackson    (entry 26906)
-- 900215 Blacksmithing  <- Kristen Smythe       (entry 26952)
-- 900216 Cooking        <- Brom Brewbaster      (entry 26905)
-- 900217 Engineering    <- Chief Engineer Leveny(entry 25277)
-- 900218 First Aid      <- Sally Tompkins       (entry 26956)
-- 900219 Fishing        <- Byron Welwick        (entry 26909)
-- 900220 Herbalism      <- Fayin Whisperleaf    (entry 26910)
-- 900221 Inscription    <- Mindri Dinkles       (entry 26916)
-- 900222 Jewelcrafting  <- Ounhulo              (entry 26915)
-- 900223 Leatherworking <- Awan Iceborn         (entry 26996)
-- 900224 Mining         <- Grumbol Stoutpick    (entry 26912)
-- 900225 Skinning       <- Frederic Burrhus     (entry 26913)
-- 900226 Tailoring      <- Benjamin Clegg       (entry 26914)
--
-- npcflag 80 = UNIT_NPC_FLAG_TRAINER (16) | UNIT_NPC_FLAG_TRAINER_PROFESSION
-- (64) - no GOSSIP bit. A trainer-only npcflag with no GOSSIP bit opens the
-- trainer window straight away on right-click, no gossip step at all -
-- deliberately avoiding the generic shared gossip_menu_id pool, which
-- bundles in unrelated options (unlearn talents, dual talent
-- specialization) for any UNIT_NPC_FLAG_TRAINER creature using that
-- default.
--
-- unit_flags 770 = UNIT_FLAG_NON_ATTACKABLE (0x2) | UNIT_FLAG_IMMUNE_TO_PC
-- (0x100) | UNIT_FLAG_IMMUNE_TO_NPC (0x200): each of these follows the
-- player through potentially hostile areas and needs the fuller set -
-- without it, a following summon gets pulled into combat by nearby
-- hostile creatures and abandons the player to run back to its spawn
-- point.
DELETE FROM `creature_template` WHERE `entry` BETWEEN 900213 AND 900226;

DELETE FROM `creature_template_model` WHERE `CreatureID` BETWEEN 900213 AND 900226;

DELETE FROM `creature_default_trainer` WHERE `CreatureId` BETWEEN 900213 AND 900226;
DELETE FROM `trainer_spell` WHERE `TrainerId` BETWEEN 900213 AND 900226;
DELETE FROM `trainer` WHERE `Id` BETWEEN 900213 AND 900226;

-- Type 2 = Tradeskill (see Trainer::Type in Trainer.h)



-- Free training at every premium profession trainer. The MoneyCost values
-- above are kept as the real, verbatim per-spell costs (in case the real
-- costs are ever wanted again - just delete this UPDATE) rather than
-- zeroed inline, since this UPDATE only ever touches our own 14 TrainerIds
-- (900213-900226) - confirmed via Trainer.cpp's TeachSpell, MoneyCost is
-- looked up per-TrainerId/SpellId pair with no cross-trainer sharing, so
-- this can never discount or zero any real trainer's cost.
UPDATE `trainer_spell` SET `MoneyCost` = 0 WHERE `TrainerId` BETWEEN 900213 AND 900226;
